bug.short_desc: CTags parsing problem: java.lang.NumberFormatException: For input string: "32481035625525327"

long_desc.thetext:
Created attachment 4023 one example of not understood java-file
I used opengrok 0.9 compiled from source using patches from https://defect.opensolaris.org/bz/show_bug.cgi?id=15956
1.) some normal java Files didn't understand by Indexer 2.) *.properties Files didn't understand by Indexer 3.) *.sh Files didn't understand by Indexer 4.) *.apt Files didn't understand by Indexer -> Maven documentation files
to 4.) I understand, that not all file-formats can be known by the indexer, but than they should be indexed as plain text-files, when they are not marked as binary.

1) attached file was indexed and properly detected for me ... what is your exuberant ctags version ? (I use 5.8)
Added: /15994/ClassFilter.java (JavaAnalyzer)
2) properties files are usually analyzed by plain analyzer, what did the "Added:" say ? What was the exception reported ?
3) sh scripts are detected upon their extension and magic strings - e.g. they begin with ## !# , ... (http://src.opensolaris.org/source/xref/opengrok/trunk/src/org/opensolaris/opengrok/analysis/sh/ShAnalyzerFactory.java#36 )
so it can very well be that if your script has e.g. wrong header it will be considered plain text (but should still be indexed, just highlighting will be wrong) you can use option -A ( http://src.opensolaris.org/source/xref/opengrok/trunk/src/org/opensolaris/opengrok/index/CommandLineOptions.java#94 ) to explicitly say which analyzer should be used for a non standard extension ( e.g. -A KSHLIB:org.opensolaris.opengrok.analysis.sh.ShAnalyzerFactory ) , if you have an extension that is standard and opengrok is not aware about it, then we shall add it to shanalyzer ...
4) for this we could file a bug(enhancement), but analyzer should discover that it's a plaintext at least(if it is plaintext ;) ) ... can you attach a sample .apt file please ?

From the stack trace, it looks like this is a line number reported by ctags. I suppose you don't have any file that big... So it seems either ctags is reporting incorrect line numbers or we are somehow misinterpreting the output from ctags.

(In reply to comment #17) > Created an attachment (id=4033) [details] > file producing Unexpected end of file
this worked for me with ctags 5.8 it's actually a bit tricky, since if I remember correctly we fork ctags as daemon and pass text buffers with code to it
it can happen that one of the files will trigger empty tags, but I guess one can ignore this, since it's a normal and expected message why is it printed then ? because there was a bug where we didn't consume this stderr buffer and it caused a deadlock on OS level, so now we consume this buffer and print it when done, this way one sees possible errors from ctags and can act upon them
the unexpected end of file is a harmless one
so I guess we're down to the weird ctags line number bug, I am going to rename this bug to fit this and disown it, since I don't have cycles to work it now :(
